<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<section xml:id="section-last-lecture-review" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Logic</title>
  <p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <term>Statements</term>: A statement is an assertion that can be either true or false (but not both).
        
       <example>
        <p>
        I enjoy reading and running. 
        </p>
       </example>

       <example>
        <p>
        4+5=9.
        </p>
       </example>
       Non-examples include questions, commands,
        and open sentences such as <m>x+5=9</m>. :contentReference[oaicite:0]{index=0}
      </li>

      <li>
        <term>Simple statements</term> do not contain other statements as parts. We use lowercase letters
        (<m>p,q,r,s,\ldots</m>) to represent simple statements (for example, <m>p</m> = “I enjoy reading” and
        <m>q</m> = “I enjoy running”). :contentReference[oaicite:1]{index=1}
      </li>

      <li>
        <term>Connectives</term> combine simple statements into compound statements (for example, conjunction “and”
        and disjunction “or”), using standard logical symbols. :contentReference[oaicite:2]{index=2}
      </li>

      <li>
        <term>Translating</term> between English and symbols: for instance, assigning symbols to statements
        (like <m>s</m>, <m>r</m>, <m>w</m>) and writing an “if … then …” statement symbolically. :contentReference[oaicite:3]{index=3}
      </li>

      <li>
        <term>Negation</term> (<m>\lnot</m>) reverses a statement’s truth value and is not a connective.
        Example: if <m>p</m> is “I enjoy running,” then <m>\lnot p</m> is “I don’t enjoy running.” :contentReference[oaicite:4]{index=4}
      </li>

      <li>
        <term>Truth tables</term> summarize all possible truth values of a statement. Negation reverses truth values.
        The conjunction rule: <m>p\land q</m> is true only when both <m>p</m> and <m>q</m> are true.
        The disjunction rule: <m>p\lor q</m> is false only when both <m>p</m> and <m>q</m> are false (inclusive “or”). :contentReference[oaicite:5]{index=5}
      </li>

      <li>
        <term>Conditional statements</term> have the form <m>p\to q</m>, where <m>p</m> is the antecedent and <m>q</m>
        is the consequent. A conditional is false only when <m>p</m> is true and <m>q</m> is false. :contentReference[oaicite:6]{index=6}
      </li>

      <li>
        <term>Logical equivalence</term>: two statements are logically equivalent when their truth tables are identical,
        for example <m>p</m> and <m>\lnot(\lnot p)</m>. :contentReference[oaicite:7]{index=7}
      </li>

      <li>
        <term>De Morgan’s Laws</term>:
        <m>\lnot(p\land q)\equiv (\lnot p)\lor(\lnot q)</m> and
        <m>\lnot(p\lor q)\equiv (\lnot p)\land(\lnot q)</m>. :contentReference[oaicite:8]{index=8}
      </li>

      <li>
        <term>Negating a conditional</term>:
        the negation of “if <m>p</m> then <m>q</m>” is “<m>p</m> and not <m>q</m>,” i.e. <m>p\land \lnot q</m>. :contentReference[oaicite:9]{index=9}
      </li>

      <li>
        <term>Related conditionals</term>: the converse, inverse, and contrapositive of a conditional, and the key fact
        that a conditional is logically equivalent to its contrapositive. :contentReference[oaicite:10]{index=10}
      </li>

      <li>
        <term>Logical arguments</term>: an argument is premises followed by a conclusion; it is valid if whenever the premises
        are true, the conclusion must be true. :contentReference[oaicite:11]{index=11}
      </li>

      <li>
        <term>Quantifiers</term>: universal quantifiers (all, every, no one) and existential quantifiers (some, there exists),
        with examples. :contentReference[oaicite:12]{index=12}
      </li>

      <li>
        <term>Set theory</term>: a set is a collection of objects (elements), with membership notation such as
        “<m>x\in S</m>.” :contentReference[oaicite:13]{index=13}
      </li>
    </ul>
  </p>

</section>





<subsection xml:id="subsec-Exercises">
  <title>Exercises</title>
  
  <exercise xml:id="ex-english-to-symbolic">
    <title>Convert English Statements into Symbols</title>

    <statement>
      <p>
        Convert each compound statement into a symbolic statement. For each part,
        assign symbols to each simple statement (for example,
        <m>f</m> = “my favorite dish has lots of anchovies”), then use the appropriate
        connectives (<m>\land</m>, <m>\lor</m>, <m>\lnot</m>, <m>\to</m>).
      </p>
    </statement>

    <task xml:id="ex-english-to-symbolic-a">
      <statement>
        <p> Jim is a lawyer, yet he is not a crook.</p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task xml:id="ex-english-to-symbolic-b">
      <statement>
        <p> Although our professor is young, he is knowledgeable.</p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task xml:id="ex-english-to-symbolic-c">
      <statement>
        <p>
           My favorite dish has lots of anchovies or is not spicy and also it comes in a large portion.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>


    <task xml:id="ex-english-to-symbolic-d">
      <statement>
        <p>
           My favorite dish has lots of anchovies and it comes in a large portion or it is spicy and it also comes in a large portion.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task xml:id="ex-english-to-symbolic-e">
      <statement>
        <p>
           If you do not attend class, then either you read a book or you will not pass the exam.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task xml:id="ex-english-to-symbolic-f">
      <statement>
        <p>
           I am doing a web search for pages containing the terms “global warming”, but not for pages containing both “termites” and “cattle”.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task xml:id="ex-english-to-symbolic-g">
      <statement>
        <p>
         I am doing a web search for pages containing the terms “global warming”, but not for pages containing the word “termites” and not for pages containing the word “cattle”.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

  </exercise>


  <exercise xml:id="ex-symbolic-to-english">
    <title>Convert Symbols into Words</title>

    <statement>
      <p>
        Convert each symbolic statement into words, given:
        <m>s</m> = The sunroof is extra,
        <m>r</m> = The radial tires are included,
        <m>w</m> = Power windows are optional.
      </p>
    </statement>

    <task xml:id="ex-symbolic-to-english-a">
      <statement>
        <p> <m>(s \land w) \to r</m>.</p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task xml:id="ex-symbolic-to-english-b">
      <statement>
        <p> <m>r \land \bigl(s \lor (\lnot w)\bigr)</m>.</p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task xml:id="ex-symbolic-to-english-c">
      <statement>
        <p> <m>(\lnot r) \to \bigl((\lnot s) \lor (\lnot w)\bigr)</m>.</p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task xml:id="ex-symbolic-to-english-d">
      <statement>
        <p> <m>\lnot(w \land s)</m>.</p>
      </statement>
    </task>

  </exercise>


    <subection xml:id="subsection-symbolic-to-english2">
  <title>Convert Symbols into Words</title>

  <p>
    In the following exercises, convert each symbolic statement into words, given:
    <m>s</m> = The sunroof is extra,
    <m>r</m> = The radial tires are included,
    <m>w</m> = Power windows are optional.
  </p>

  <question xml:id="ex-symbolic-to-english-a2">
    <statement>
      <p><m>(s \land w) \to r</m>.</p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        If the sunroof is extra and the power windows are optional, then the radial tires
        are included.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </question>

  <question xml:id="ex-symbolic-to-english-b2">
    <statement>
      <p><m>r \land \bigl(s \lor (\lnot w)\bigr)</m>.</p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        The radial tires are included, and either the sunroof is extra or the power
        windows are not optional.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </question>

  <question xml:id="ex-symbolic-to-english-c2">
    <statement>
      <p><m>(\lnot r) \to \bigl((\lnot s) \lor (\lnot w)\bigr)</m>.</p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        If the radial tires are not included, then either the sunroof is not extra or
        the power windows are not optional.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </question>

  <question xml:id="ex-symbolic-to-english-d2">
    <statement>
      <p><m>\lnot(w \land s)</m>.</p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        It is not the case that the power windows are optional and the sunroof is extra.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </question>

</subsection>
